CDC publish allergy guidelines for schools
The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) published on Wednesday a set of guidelines for the treatment of children with food allergies in schools.
These are the first such guidelines issued by the American government has, since the number of school children with food allergies is on the rise.
One in 20 children in the United States now has a food allergy.
According to the CDC, the distribution of food allergies among children has increased by 18 percent between 1997 and 2007.
